mpany said it expected earnings for the quarter tobe below analysts' forecasts.   The stock fell $6 a share Wednesday to close at $111.50 on heavyvolume of more than 5 million shares.   Besides its quarterly troubles, IBM said that if the effects ofthe stronger dollar and the shift to leasing by IBM customerscontinues for the rest of 1989, ``it will also be difficult for IBMto achieve full-year results within the current range ofestimates.''</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Paul A. Bilzerian, the corporate raiderconvicted of engineering a series of illegal stock deals, wassentenced to four years in prison and fined $1.5 million in thestiffest sentence of the government's three-year Wall Street fraudcrackdown.   Bilzerian, a high-school dropout and Vietnam veteran who cappeda meteoric business career with the $1.06 billion takeover ofSinger Co., was convicted June 9 on nine counts of securitiesfraud, conspiracy to commit tax fraud and making false statementsto the government. He was sentenced Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A slowdown in public works projects helped pushthe level of new construction contracts down 3 percent in August, asurvey found.   The latest setback followed a brief period of stabilitynationwide for new construction of all types, according to the F.W.Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information Services Co., which releasedthe survey Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush urged Western nations toincrease their financial support for Poland, and a top Polishofficial appealed for $1.5 billion to help his nation cope with aperiod of ``potentially explosive social conditions.''   In his first address to the annual meetings of the InternationalMonetary Fund and World Bank, Bush on Wednesday praised the effortsof the Solidarity-led government to handle the economic crisisfacing Poland.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Citizens andamp; Southern Corp. of Atlanta said itsmerger with Virginia-based Sovran Financial Corp. creating thenation's 14th-largest banking company was not a reaction to anearlier hostile bid by NCNB Corp.   ``This is not a reactionary thing. ... We started conversations(with Sovran) two years ago,'' Bennett A. Brown, Candamp;S chairman anddesignated chief executive officer of the new combined company,told a meeting of securities analysts Wednesday in New York.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A high-fiber, zero-calorie flour substitute anda plastic engine are among the winners of this year's Randamp;D 100awards for inventions, Research and Development magazine said.   Other winners chosen by the magazine and announced Wednesdayinclude a miniaturized television or computer screen that fits overone eye, a device that converts letters on a computer screen toBraille, and a system for making sure infants are getting enoughoxygen to their brains.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices finished mixed Wednesday as the Dow Jones averageof 30 industrials closed with a 9.12 gain at 2,673.06.   Bond prices fell modestly.   The dollar fell amid more dollar-selling by central banks.   Grain futures prices fell, crude oil futures rose, wheat priceswere mixed, livestock and pork fell, and precious metals declined.</TEXT></DOC>